The morning time of day indicator variable (D
               1t
               ) has a negative but insignificant coefficient, and the late afternoon time of day indicator variable (D
               2t
               ) has a significantly negative coefficient. This indicates that, relative to mid‐day, floor trades are more likely in the morning and afternoon. There are two factors at play here: (1) there is evidence that the markets are more liquid during the morning and afternoon hours than during midday (see, e.g., Jain and Joh1988), and (2) floor traders who may be willing to be patient earlier in the trading day are more apt to step forth and trade as the closing bell approaches so as to avoid carrying an open position into the overnight period.
